BREAKING: CDC Gives Final Approval for  COVID-19 Shots for Kids 5 to 11

@COVID19Up: US CDC Director Rochelle Walensky has given the final approval tonight (Nov. 2) to Pfizer's COVID-19 vaccine for children aged 5-11.

The announcement came just hours after a CDC advisory panel unanimously decided Pfizer‚Äôs jabs should be given to children aged 5 to 11. 

A week ago, Harvard doctor Eric Rubin on an FDA panel discussion said, "we're never going to learn how safe this vaccine is until we start giving it." Now we will start to learn how safe it is for kids.

The safety tests for the Pfizer kids vaccine involved less than 2,500 children. There are 28 million children aged 5-11 in the United States. 

There are further plans for Pfizer to develop additional vaccines for children all the way down to the age of six months. 

The control group for the safety tests was a group of children aged 16-25, as noted in Pfizer's press release.  The data from the safety tests is not publicly available but was shared with the FDA.  Only general summaries of the safety data, written by Pfizer, are available to the public. 

Pfizer has shipped millions of doses to governments, doctors and pharmacies.

The kid shots contain a third of the dose given to adults.

Pfizer expects to sell about $36 billion of COVID vaccines this year.
